<subSubSection id="AAA46576FFBEFFD16CA8FCA3E1EB2171" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E20136FDFFBEFFD16CA8FCA3E1EB2171" blockId="4.[151,1437,690,1869]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16CA8FCA3E52C26E0" bold="true" box="[199,322,870,896]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognized among species of 
<taxonomicName id="25BE4D7EFFBEFFD16ECFFCA2E77E26E1" box="[672,784,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Corixidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16ECFFCA2E77E26E1" box="[672,784,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Corixidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the uniformly dark coloration, macropterous forewing without a pale band (
<figureCitation id="7A852A78FFBEFFD16DE5FC4EE58326C5" box="[394,493,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1952,1976]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1929]" captionTargetId="figure-217@3.[151,1436,597,1929]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus of Corixidea graziae sp. nov., Corixidea quilombola sp. nov., and Schizoptera (Cantharocoris) savannensis sp. nov. in dorsal, ventral, and lateral views. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691704/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Figure 2</figureCitation>
), mediotergite 8 asymmetrical, with process insertion on the left side (
<figureCitation id="7A852A78FFBEFFD16978FC4EE1E026C5" box="[1303,1422,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1822,1846]" captionTargetBox="[169,1429,604,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-109@5.[151,1436,597,1798]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalic features. A. Corixidea graziae sp. nov. B. Corixidea quilombola sp. nov. C–D. Schizoptera (Cantharocoris) savannensis sp. nov. C. Ventral view of abdominal apex; black arrow points to posterior process of sternum 6 and white arrow points to lateral process of subgenital plate. D. Dorsal view. Abbreviations: lca = left conjunctival appendage, lp = left paramere, rca = right conjunctival appendage, rp = right paramere, st6 = sternum 6, st7 = sternum 7 (subgenital plate), mt8 = mediotergite 8, mt8p = mediotergite 8 process, py = pygophore, v = vesica. Scale bars: A–B = 0.1 mm, B–C = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691708/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
), process of mediotergite 8 anteriorly directed, composed of an elongate projection mostly covered with many small pointed projections and a widened triangular plate-like base (
<figureCitation id="7A852A78FFBEFFD16F3BFC16E7A5268D" box="[852,971,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1822,1846]" captionTargetBox="[169,1429,604,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-109@5.[151,1436,597,1798]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalic features. A. Corixidea graziae sp. nov. B. Corixidea quilombola sp. nov. C–D. Schizoptera (Cantharocoris) savannensis sp. nov. C. Ventral view of abdominal apex; black arrow points to posterior process of sternum 6 and white arrow points to lateral process of subgenital plate. D. Dorsal view. Abbreviations: lca = left conjunctival appendage, lp = left paramere, rca = right conjunctival appendage, rp = right paramere, st6 = sternum 6, st7 = sternum 7 (subgenital plate), mt8 = mediotergite 8, mt8p = mediotergite 8 process, py = pygophore, v = vesica. Scale bars: A–B = 0.1 mm, B–C = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691708/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
); right paramere elongate and narrowed, strongly arched, bearing a small claw-like projection and a cluster of four small fine setae on the tip (
<figureCitation id="7A852A78FFBEFFD1696DFC32E1162171" box="[1282,1400,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1822,1846]" captionTargetBox="[169,1429,604,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-109@5.[151,1436,597,1798]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalic features. A. Corixidea graziae sp. nov. B. Corixidea quilombola sp. nov. C–D. Schizoptera (Cantharocoris) savannensis sp. nov. C. Ventral view of abdominal apex; black arrow points to posterior process of sternum 6 and white arrow points to lateral process of subgenital plate. D. Dorsal view. Abbreviations: lca = left conjunctival appendage, lp = left paramere, rca = right conjunctival appendage, rp = right paramere, st6 = sternum 6, st7 = sternum 7 (subgenital plate), mt8 = mediotergite 8, mt8p = mediotergite 8 process, py = pygophore, v = vesica. Scale bars: A–B = 0.1 mm, B–C = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691708/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AAA46576FFBEFFD16CA8FBDFE0B92085" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" type="description">
<paragraph id="E20136FDFFBEFFD16CA8FBDFE0B92085" blockId="4.[151,1437,690,1869]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16CA8FBDFE5F02155" bold="true" box="[199,414,1050,1077]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Description. Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="7A852A78FFBEFFD16DC2FBDEE67E2155" box="[429,528,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1952,1976]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1929]" captionTargetId="figure-217@3.[151,1436,597,1929]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus of Corixidea graziae sp. nov., Corixidea quilombola sp. nov., and Schizoptera (Cantharocoris) savannensis sp. nov. in dorsal, ventral, and lateral views. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691704/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Figure 2</figureCitation>
): macropterous, body elongate-oval. 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16FDAFBDFE0512154" bold="true" box="[949,1087,1050,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Coloration:</emphasis>
general coloration dark brown and costal area of the forewing dark brown to black, remainder of wing dark brown, antenna and legs uniformly yellow, abdomen dark brown. 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16D9DFBA7E693211C" bold="true" box="[498,765,1122,1149]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Surface and vestiture:</emphasis>
head, pronotum, and wing veins with medium-length light brown setae, abdomen densely covered with elongate, light brown setae. 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16F81FB43E0D321C1" bold="true" box="[1006,1213,1158,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Structure: Head:</emphasis>
rounded in ventral view, width of eye about 1/3 width of synthlipsis, ocellus about the same size to one ommatidium, placed close to the lateral margin of compound eye. 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16E04FB0AE6A32189" bold="true" box="[619,717,1231,1257]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Thorax:</emphasis>
pronotum trapezoidal, with posterior margin slightly concave medially, scutellum triangular, with a rounded tip, hind coxa with well-developed adhesive pad, tarsal formula 3- 3-3. 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16CA3FAD3E5242050" bold="true" box="[204,330,1302,1328]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Abdomen:</emphasis>
with six visible sterna corresponding to segments 2+3, 4, 5, 6, 7, and pygophore. Mediotergite 8 asymmetrical, with process insertion on the left side. Process of mediotergite 8 anteriorly directed, composed of an elongate projection mostly covered with many small pointed projections and a widened triangular plate-like base. 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16CF8FA47E56B20FC" bold="true" box="[151,261,1410,1436]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="7A852A78FFBEFFD16D77FA46E5FC20FD" box="[280,402,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1822,1846]" captionTargetBox="[169,1429,604,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-109@5.[151,1436,597,1798]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalic features. A. Corixidea graziae sp. nov. B. Corixidea quilombola sp. nov. C–D. Schizoptera (Cantharocoris) savannensis sp. nov. C. Ventral view of abdominal apex; black arrow points to posterior process of sternum 6 and white arrow points to lateral process of subgenital plate. D. Dorsal view. Abbreviations: lca = left conjunctival appendage, lp = left paramere, rca = right conjunctival appendage, rp = right paramere, st6 = sternum 6, st7 = sternum 7 (subgenital plate), mt8 = mediotergite 8, mt8p = mediotergite 8 process, py = pygophore, v = vesica. Scale bars: A–B = 0.1 mm, B–C = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691708/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
): Pygophore asymmetrical and almost triangular. Left paramere triangular and plate-like. Right paramere elongate and narrowed, strongly arched, bearing a small claw-like projection and a cluster of four small fine setae on the tip. Aedeagus long and thin, without processes. Anophoric process absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AAA46576FFBEFFD16CA8FA2AE7542315" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E20136FDFFBEFFD16CA8FA2AE7542315" blockId="4.[151,1437,690,1869]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16CA8FA2AE5202369" bold="true" box="[199,334,1519,1545]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet quilombola refers to people who inhabit quilombo communities. Quilombos are Black rural communities made by the descendants of African-American slaves, who live, in their majority, from subsistence agriculture. They are founded mainly during colonial Portuguese rule in 
<collectingCountry id="9AA9766DFFBEFFD1681EF9F2E0DB2331" box="[1137,1205,1591,1617]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(between 1530 and 1815) by escaped slaves. This species’ name is indeclinable.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AAA46576FFBEFFD16CA8F9BBE67023F9" box="[199,542,1662,1689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E20136FDFFBEFFD16CA8F9BBE67023F9" blockId="4.[151,1437,690,1869]" box="[199,542,1662,1689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16CA8F9BBE50F23F8" bold="true" box="[199,353,1662,1688]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="9AA9766DFFBEFFD16D08F9BAE5C523F9" box="[359,427,1663,1689]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="207AF81FFFBEFFD16DD4F9BAE67C23F9" box="[443,530,1663,1689]" country="Brazil" name="Amapa" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Amapá</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AAA46576FFBEFFD16CA8F966E02C222D" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="E20136FDFFBEFFD16CA8F966E02C222D" blockId="4.[151,1437,690,1869]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16CA8F966E55523DD" bold="true" box="[199,315,1699,1725]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="25BE4D7EFFBEFFD16EC6F966E03823DD" authority="Emsley, 1969" authorityName="Emsley" authorityYear="1969" box="[681,1110,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Corixidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="underwoodii">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16EC6F966E7DF23DD" box="[681,945,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Corixidea underwoodii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="862F4B0CFFBEFFD16FD4F966E03823DD" author="Emsley, M. G." box="[955,1110,1699,1725]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" pagination="1 - 154" refId="ref4419" refString="Emsley, M. G. (1969) The Schizopteridae (Hemiptera: Heteroptera) with the descriptions of new species from Trinidad. Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 25, 1 - 154." type="journal article" year="1969">Emsley, 1969</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="9AA9766DFFBEFFD168CFF966E11323DD" box="[1184,1405,1699,1725]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">Trinidad &amp; Tobago</collectingCountry>
in having a very long and anteriorly directed process of mediotergite 8. However, in 
<taxonomicName id="25BE4D7EFFBEFFD16832F902E16F2381" authority="Albuquerque &amp; De-Souza &amp; Favacho &amp; Carvalho-Filho, 2021" authorityName="Albuquerque &amp; De-Souza &amp; Favacho &amp; Carvalho-Filho" authorityYear="2021" box="[1117,1281,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Corixidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quilombola" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16832F902E16F2381" box="[1117,1281,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">C. quilombola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16964F902E1062381" bold="true" box="[1291,1384,1735,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="CBF95794FFBEFFD16964F902E1062381" box="[1291,1384,1735,1761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the process of mediotergite 8 is mostly covered with many small pointed projections, while in 
<taxonomicName id="25BE4D7EFFBEFFD168FBF92EE12D2265" authorityName="Emsley" authorityYear="1969" box="[1172,1347,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Corixidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="underwoodii">
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD168FBF92EE12D2265" box="[1172,1347,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">C. underwoodii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it bears tiny setulae on the tip and basally. These species belong to one of the two subgroups of the 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD168DFF8CAE0972248" box="[1200,1273,1807,1832]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">crassa</emphasis>
species group because they have an anteriorly directed process of tergum 8 (
<bibRefCitation id="862F4B0CFFBEFFD16F23F8F6E058222D" author="Knyshov, A. &amp; Hoey-Chamberlain, R. &amp; Weirauch, C." box="[844,1078,1843,1869]" pageId="4" pageNumber="256" pagination="985 - 995" refId="ref4752" refString="Knyshov, A., Hoey-Chamberlain, R. &amp; Weirauch, C. (2019) Hybrid enrichment of poorly preserved museum specimens refines homology hypotheses in a group of minute litter bugs (Hemiptera: Dipsocoromorpha: Schizopteridae). Systematic Entomology, 44 (4), 985 - 995. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12368" type="journal article" year="2019">
Knyshov 
<emphasis id="D0CAEAEFFFBEFFD16FD5F8F6E79C222D" box="[954,1010,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="256">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
